President Obama spoke with President Kiir to urge him to continue building on the recent achievements of the nationality and citizenship agreements between South Sudan and Sudan. He expressed hope for a summit between the two countries' heads of state, as previously agreed. President Obama also expressed concern about the growing tensions and violent clashes along the shared border between South Sudan and Sudan, as well as renewed fighting in Southern Kordofan State. He emphasized the importance of avoiding unilateral actions and asked President Kiir to ensure that South Sudan's military exercises restraint and does not support fighting along the border. The President also stressed the need for South Sudan and Sudan to reach an agreement on oil. President Obama welcomed President Kiir's commitment to a summit and finding peaceful solutions for both countries.